@node Introduction
@chapter Introduction
@cpindex STREAMS

@cite{UNIX System V Release 3.2} included a Logical Link Interface (LLI) that was later standardized
as the Data Link Provider Interface (DLPI) by the @cite{Open Group}.@footnote{Evidence of this can
still be found in the @file{dlpi.h} header file distributed by @cite{The Open Group} in the DLPI
standard.  Reference is made in the header file to backward compatibility to the LLI interface.}

The Link Layer Interface (LLI) was developed by Spider Systems, Ltd., (now a division of Emerson
Power) and is widely available on many platforms.  For example, @cite{AIX AIXlink/X.25}, @cite{HP-UX
X.25/9000}, @cite{IRIX IRIS SX.25}, @cite{PT X.25}, @cite{RadiSys WAN}, @cite{SBE X.25},
@cite{Solaris SunLink X.25} and @cite{Solaris Solstice X.25}, implement the Link Layer Interface
(LLI).@footnote{But, for the most part, it is not called the @i{Link Lyaer Interface}, but is
instead sunk inside the Network Layer Interface (NLI).}

The Link Layer Interface (LLI) as designed to be used directly with standard @acronym{STREAMS} system
calls and does not require the use of a cooperating user space shared library.  Applications
programs directly use the @command{getmsg(2s)}, @command{getpmsg(2s)}, @command{putmsg(2s)},
@command{putpmsg(2s)} and @command{ioctl(2s)} system calls.@footnote{See @manref{getmsg(2s)},
@manref{getpmsg(2s)}, @manref{putmsg(2s)}, @manref{putpmsg(2s)} and @manref{ioctl(2s)} manual pages.}
Nevertheless, user shared object libraries can easily be constructed using this @acronym{STREAMS}
service primitive interface.

The system header files that must be included when compiling user applications,
or @acronym{STREAMS} drivers and modules that use the interface, are detailed in
@ref{LLI Header Files}.

A user library, @file{libsx25}, is provided, not for interfacing to the message primitive service
interface, but for providing various helper functions when using the @acronym{STREAMS} service
interface.  This library is detailed in @ref{LLI Library}.

